Ann. 12, 64, Quae filio dare imperium, tolerare imperitantem nequibat, where quibat is to be understood before dare. These two last are also from Scheller. The verb that is understood receives, in gene- ral, a colouring from the verb that is expressed3 as my most learned friend, Mr. O’Grady, has well observed. And very frequently the verb understood is the contrary of the one expressed, as in Phaed. 4, Fab. 16, Non veto dimitti, verum cruciari fame. At the second member we must understand volo, jubeo, or something similar, and not veto. This last example is from the Port Royal Grammar, p. 420, c. 1, on Fi- gures of construction, where the author of the grammar gives a va· riety from the Holy Scripture. See him and the authority to which he refers; see also Heusinger on Cic. Off. 1. c. 9, pr., where he says, Saepe unum verbum pluribus nominibus aptatur, quorum uni tantum convenit. All the nouus are joined to one verb, though it cannot go- vern them all as to the sense.
